“How wonderful it would be if my whole life so far turns out to have been a dream and suddenly I wake up and I'm someone else entirely.”

A monstrous spectacle of a movie that's as mesmerizing as it is harrowing. Incredibly dense and expertly crafted--in true Nolan fashion. But it's powerful presentation of its major beats is what makes this film truly special, almost feel like getting hit with a gut-punch. A must-see on the biggest, loudest screen possible.

A campy, dazzling, existential romp that addresses some profound social themes. Filled with fun and empathy. For a movie about plastic dolls, it's ironically, genuinely humanistic. The whole cast knocked it out of the park, but Gosling steals the show.

Movie: Mission: Impossible – Dead Reckoning Part One
Review: Tends to talk down to the audience, but makes up with its levelled up, extraordinary action set pieces. Tom Cruise is a *movie star* and should be protected at all cost.

Arguably Wes Anderson's funniest, and surprisingly, most complex and sentimental piece to date. Sharply written, visually arresting, with endearing performances by an ace ensemble cast. As Wes Anderson as it gets.
